Ecological notes : very common in all types of woodland; sandy and wet heathland; wetlands including fens, reed and sedge beds,
Cladium
beds with tufa, basin mire, quaking and raised bogs, butterbur swamp, lake and river margins and wet meadows; former gravel workings; open glen with stream; meadow hedges and ditches; pasture; common on calcareous and neutral grassland; open montane habitats; grikes; coastal shingle; grounds of horticultural research station; gardens; cabbage field. At hawthorn flowers; larvae in group at base of grass stems, adults in large swarm. Reared from the fungus
Peziza carnea
and poplar log, in laboratory. iii–xi.
